## Regional councils in North Carolina  

In **1995**, there were **18** regional councils of government operating within the state. Over the ensuing years this number decreased to **17** &#91;2&#93; and presently **North Carolina** is home to **16** such councils. &#91;3&#93;  

Regional councils in **North Carolina** are committed to collaborative action. In **2010**, the **seventeen** councils that existed at that time signed an **inter‑regional cooperative agreement** that established a policy to enhance their collective value by sharing member resources and capacity to deliver services to the state. &#91;3&#93; This agreement also endorses regional councils to carry out activities beyond their traditional boundaries, provided that such services benefit the region and the state and are undertaken with the consent of the participating entities. &#91;3&#93;  

Regional boundaries generally correspond to **county borders**, with each council comprising a coalition of both **county** and **municipal** governments. &#91;2&#93; Although the number of regional councils in **North Carolina** has declined over the years, the **number of citizens served** by these councils has continued to rise. The reduction in council count mirrors a **national trend** that saw a **20 %** decrease between **1976** and **1988**, largely driven by councils merging or absorbing smaller sub‑regional entities. &#91;1&#93;  

As of **July 1, 2007**, it was reported that the **number of local governments** served by regional councils in **North Carolina** had increased by **16 %** since **1994**. &#91;2&#93; During the same period, the **number of citizens** represented by these councils grew by **35 %**, amounting to approximately **2.3 million** individuals. &#91;2&#93; This growth translates to **92 %** of local governments and **97 %** of all **North Carolina** citizens being represented by regional councils as of that date. &#91;2&#93;  

