## Services provided by regional councils  

Regional councils of government—commonly abbreviated as **COGs**—deliver a wide array of services to their member jurisdictions. **Planning**, **technical assistance**, **geographic information systems (GIS)**, and **grant writing** rank among the most prevalent services offered throughout the **State of North Carolina**. &#91;2&#93; Much like the increase in representation from **1994** to **2007**, the **breadth of services** provided by COGs has also expanded. &#91;2&#93;  

In **1995**, only **seven** of the **18** COGs operating at that time provided **all four** of the aforementioned services. By **2008**, the number of COGs delivering the complete suite of services had risen to **17 out of 17**, or **100 %**. &#91;2&#93;  

Today, every regional council in **North Carolina** administers the **federal and state aging programs** in cooperation with the **[North Carolina Department of Environmental Quality](/North_Carolina_Department_of_Environmental_Quality) (DENR)** and the **[North Carolina Department of Transportation](/NCDOT)**. Beyond aging services, regional councils manage a broad portfolio of programs, including **transportation planning**, **Community Development Block Grant (CDBG)** allocations, **HUD grants**, **data collection**, **housing initiatives**, and more. These programs are made possible through partnerships with **federal and state agencies** such as the **[United States Department of Housing and Urban Development](/United_States_Department_of_Housing_and_Urban_Development)**, the **[Economic Development Administration](/Economic_Development_Administration)**, the **[United States Environmental Protection Agency](/United_States_Environmental_Protection_Agency)**, the **[North Carolina Department of Commerce]**, the **[United States Department of Health and Human Services](/United_States_Department_of_Health_and_Human_Services)**, and the **[North Carolina Rural Center]**. &#91;3&#93;  

The **top four services** cited as most important to local governments as of **2007**—in order—were:  

1. **Economic Development and Planning**,  
2. **Grant Writing and Administration**,  
3. **Transportation Planning**, and  
4. **Regional water resources planning**. &#91;2&#93;  

Looking ahead, projected priorities for the next **5–10 years** are expected to shift. The emerging top four services—again in order—are anticipated to be:  

1. **Regional water resources planning**,  
2. **Transportation Planning**,  
3. **Community and Economic Development Planning**, and  
4. **Grant Writing and Administration**. &#91;2&#93;  

