## Regional council budgets  

While representation and the **volume of services** delivered by COGs have risen steadily, the **budgetary allocations** for these councils have not experienced proportional growth. In general, **total budgets** have increased modestly, yet **per‑capita budgets** have declined substantially between **1994** and **2007**. &#91;2&#93; This decline reflects the fact that **population growth** in **North Carolina** has outpaced the rate of budgetary expansion. &#91;2&#93;  

The size of a council’s budget is influenced by **geographical area**, **population**, and **the scope of services** it provides. Consequently, budgets vary widely across the state. &#91;2&#93; In **2007**, **Region R**—comprising the counties of **Camden, Chowan, Currituck, Dare, Gates, Hyde, Pasquotank, Perquimans, Tyrrell, and Washington**—recorded the **smallest** budget of any regional council in the state, approximately **$4.4 million**. &#91;2&#93; By contrast, **Region I**—encompassing **Davie, Forsyth, Stokes, Surry, and Yadkin**—boasted the **largest** budget, roughly **$15.2 million**. &#91;2&#93;  

Between **1994** and **2007**, the **average total budget** for North Carolina COGs rose **11 %**, moving from **$8 million** to **$8.9 million**. &#91;2&#93; During the same interval, **direct state contributions** to regional councils decreased by **27 %**. &#91;2&#93; Over the same period, the **state’s population** grew by **26 %**. &#91;2&#93; This demographic surge, coupled with the reduction in state funding, precipitated an average **per‑capita budget decrease of 39 %**, falling from **$42** to **$26**. &#91;2&#93;  

Regional councils derive the **bulk of their financing** from **federal and state sources**. &#91;4&#93; In **1994**, it was reported that **approximately 92 %** (**$95 million**) of the **$103 million** received by regional councils originated from **State and Federal** funding. &#91;4&#93; Of this share, **84 %**—roughly **$80 million**—was **passed through** to local governments or other agencies to support services for target populations such as **housing assistance** recipients and the **elderly**. &#91;4&#93; The remaining **7 %**, or about **$8 million**, consisted of **local funding**. &#91;4&#93;  

