## State enabling statutes  

The legal foundation for regional councils in **North Carolina** is provided by **NCGS 160A‑470**, which enables the establishment of regional councils of government and extends an invitation for participation to governments in adjoining states. The statute reads, in part:  

> “(a) Any two or more units of local government may create a regional council of governments by adopting identical concurrent resolutions to that effect in accordance with the provisions and procedures of this Part. To the extent permitted by the laws of its state, a local government in a state adjoining North Carolina may participate in regional councils of governments organized under this Part to the same extent as if it were located in this State. The concurrent resolutions creating a regional council of governments and any amendments thereto, will be referred to in this Part as the *‘charter’* of the regional council”. &#91;5&#93;  

**NCGS 160‑475** further enumerates the specific powers conferred upon regional councils via their charter. These powers include, but are not limited to:  

* **(1)** Applying for, accepting, receiving, and dispensing funds and grants from the **State of North Carolina**, any agency thereof, the **United States of America**, any agency thereof, any unit of local government (whether or not a member of the council), and any private or civic agency;  
* **(2)** Employing personnel;  
* **(3)** Contracting with consultants;  
* **(4)** Contracting with the **State of North Carolina**, any other state, the **United States of America**, or any agency thereof for services;  
* **(5)** Studying regional governmental problems, including matters affecting health, safety, welfare, education, recreation, economic conditions, regional planning, and regional development;  
* **(6)** Promoting cooperative arrangements and coordinated action among its member governments;  
* **(7)** Making recommendations for review and action to its member governments and other public agencies that perform functions within the region;  
* **(7a)** Acquiring real property, by purchase, gift, or otherwise, to meet office‑space and program needs, and pledging real property as security for indebtedness used to finance acquisition or improvements, subject to approval by the **Local Government Commission** as required under **G.S. 159‑153**; a regional council may **not** exercise the power of eminent domain;  
* **(8)** Exercising any other powers that are exercised or capable of being exercised by its member governments and are desirable for addressing problems of mutual concern, provided such powers are specifically delegated by resolution of the governing board of each affected member government. &#91;5&#93;  

